'''Corine Schleif''' is a [[professor]] and [[art historian]] who researches, teaches and writes about [[Medieval art]], [[Renaissance art]], [[feminist art theory]], and the motivations behind the creating and destroying of art. She is faculty at [[Arizona State University]]'s School of Art.<ref>{{cite web|title=Corine Schleif {{!}} School of Art|url=https://art.asu.edu/profile/corine-schleif|website=art.asu.edu|language=en}}</ref>
== Education and career == Corine Schleif studied [[art history]] at [[University of Marburg|Philipp University of Marburg]] and went on to [[Washington University in St. Louis]] to receive an M.A. in 1980. She then attended [[Free University of Berlin]] with a [[Fulbright scholarship]] which was renewed at [[Ludwig Maximilians University of Munich]]. She received her Doctorate (Dr. phil.) in art history ([[medieval history]] and [[religious studies]] minors) from [[University of Bamberg]] in 1986. In addition to being a Professor at ASU's School of Art, she is an Affiliate Professor at the [[Arizona Center for Medieval and Renaissance Studies]] (ACMRS).<ref>{{cite web|title=Faculty Spotlight: ACMRS Affiliate Prof. Corine Schleif {{!}} ACMRS|url=https://acmrs.org/news/faculty-spotlight-acmrs-affiliate-prof-corine-schleif|website=acmrs.org}}</ref>
Schleif received the [[Berlin Prize]] from the [[American Academy in Berlin|American Academy]] as the John P. Birkelund Fellow in the Humanities for the Class of Spring 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Corine Schleif - American Academy|url=http://www.americanacademy.de/person/corine-schleif/|website=American Academy}}</ref>
Schleif's recent work has included ''opening the [[Arizona Center for Medieval and Renaissance Studies#The Geese Book|Geese Book]]'': "A multisensory work of the past is explored through multimedia technologies of the present. A team of experts headed by Volker Schier and Corine Schleif opens the Geese Book to scholars and provides a window for broader audiences."<ref>{{cite web|title=opening the Geese Book|url=http://geesebook.asu.edu/|website=geesebook.asu.edu}}</ref> She and Schier also developed a [[Virtual reality]] (VR) experience called ''Extraordinary Sensescapes: The Sensual World of Late Medieval Nuns''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Extraordinary Sensescapes|url=http://sensescapes.asu.edu/|website=sensescapes.asu.edu}}</ref>
