{{About||a non-technical introduction to genetics in general|Introduction to genetics|Paleo-Indian lineages associated with the first peopling of the Americas|Settlement of the Americas#Genomic age estimates}}

[[File:World Map of Y-DNA Haplogroups.png|upright=1.75|thumb|Possible migration routes to the Americas as predicted by the distribution of Y-DNA haplogroups: inland route (purple lines), Pacific coastal route (brown dashed line), and possible trans-Atlantic route (light blue double line).]]
The [[genetic history]] of   [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas]] (also named '''Amerindians''' or '''Amerinds''' in physical anthropology) is divided into two sharply distinct episodes: 
the [[Prehistoric migration and settlement of the Americas from Asia|initial peopling of the Americas]] during about 20,000 to 14,000 years ago (20&ndash;14 kya), and [[European colonization of the Americas|European contact]], after about 500 years ago.<ref name=Genebase/><ref>{{cite journal |last=Orgel |first=Leslie E. |title=Prebiotic chemistry and the origin of the RNA world |journal=[[Critical Reviews in Biochemistry and Molecular Biology]] |volume=39 |issue=2 |pages=99–123 | url=http://www.d.umn.edu/~pschoff/documents/OrgelRNAWorld.pdf |pmid=15217990 |doi=10.1080/10409230490460765 |year=2004|citeseerx=10.1.1.537.7679 }}</ref> The former is the determinant factor for the number of genetic lineages, [[zygosity]] mutations and founding [[haplotype]]s present in today's [[Population history of indigenous peoples of the Americas|Indigenous Amerindian populations]].<ref name="KleinmanMoore2014">{{cite book |first=Kim |last=Tallbear |chapter=The Emergence, Politics, and Marketplace of Native American DNA  |editor-first1=Daniel Lee |editor-last1=Kleinman |editor-first2=Kelly |editor-last2=Moore |title=Routledge Handbook of Science, Technology, and Society |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gqDAAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA23 |year=2014 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-136-23716-4 |page=23}}</ref>

Most Amerindians groups are derived from a basal '''Ancestral lineage''', which formed in [[Siberia]] prior to the [[Last Glacial Maximum]], between about 36,000 and 25,000 years ago, from a combination of  [[Proto-Mongoloid]]  and [[Ancient North Eurasian]] ancestry and which dispersed throughout the Americas after about 16,000 years ago (an exception are the [[Na Dene]] and [[Eskimo–Aleut languages|Eskimo–Aleut]] speaking groups, which are partially derived from Siberian populations which entered the Americas at a later time).<ref name="Moreno-Mayar2018">{{Citation| title = Terminal Pleistocene Alaskan genome reveals first founding population of Native Americans | url = https://www.nature.com/articles/nature25173 | journal  = Nature | volume = 553 | issue = 7687 | pages = 203–207 | accessdate = January 3, 2018 | doi = 10.1038/nature25173 | pmid = 29323294 | year = 2018 | last1 = Moreno-Mayar | first1 = J. Víctor | last2 = Potter | first2 = Ben A. | last3 = Vinner | first3 = Lasse | last4 = Steinrücken | first4 = Matthias | last5 = Rasmussen | first5 = Simon | last6 = Terhorst | first6 = Jonathan | last7 = Kamm | first7 = John A. | last8 = Albrechtsen | first8 = Anders | last9 = Malaspinas | first9 = Anna-Sapfo | last10 = Sikora | first10 = Martin | last11 = Reuther | first11 = Joshua D. | last12 = Irish | first12 = Joel D. | last13 = Malhi | first13 = Ripan S. | last14 = Orlando | first14 = Ludovic | last15 = Song | first15 = Yun S. | last16 = Nielsen | first16 = Rasmus | last17 = Meltzer | first17 = David J. | last18 = Willerslev | first18 = Eske }}
Confidence intervals given in Moreno-Mayar et al. (2018):
26.1-23-9 kya for the separation of the East Asian lineage of ANA from modern East Asian populations;
25-20 kya for the admixture event of ANE and early East Asian lineages ancestral to ANA;
22.0-18.1 kya for the separation of Ancient Beringian from other Paleo-Indian lineages;
17.5-14.6 kya for the separation of Paleo Indian into North Native Americans (NNA) and South Native Americans (SNA). [https://media.nature.com/original/nature-assets/nature/journal/v553/n7687/extref/nature25173-s2.pdf Supplementary Material] p. 37. "the admixture event that gave rise to most Na-Dene-speakers, between NNA and a Siberian population occurred well after 11.5 kya and at least prior to ~2.5 kya".</ref>

In the early 2000s, archaeogenetics was primarily based on [[Human Y-chromosome DNA haplogroup]]s and [[Human mitochondrial DNA haplogroup]]s.<ref name=nomenclature>{{cite journal |year=2002 |last1=Y Chromosome Consortium |url=http://genome.cshlp.org/content/12/2/339.full.pdf |title=A Nomenclature System for the Tree of Human Y-Chromosomal Binary Haplogroups |journal=[[Genome Research]] |pmid=11827954 |volume=12 |issue=2 |pmc=155271 |pages=339–348 |doi=10.1101/gr.217602}}[http://genome.cshlp.org/content/12/2/339/F1.large.jpg (Detailed hierarchical chart)]</ref> [[Autosome|Autosomal]] "atDNA" markers are also used, but differ from mtDNA or Y-DNA in that they overlap significantly.<ref name=Griffiths>{{Cite book |editor-last1=Griffiths |editor-first1=Anthony J. F. |editor-first2=Jeffrey H. |editor-last2=Miller |editor-first3=David T. |editor-last3=Suzuki |editor-first4=Richard C. |editor-last4=Lewontin |editor-first5=William M. |editor-last5=Gelbart |display-editors=3 |title=An Introduction to Genetic Analysis |year=2000 |edition=7th |publisher=W.H. Freeman |location=New York |isbn=978-0-7167-3771-1 |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/bv.fcgi?highlight=autosome&rid=iga.section.222}}
{{clarify|date=July 2018}}<!--what exactly is this supposed to reference? page number?--></ref>

Analyses of genetics among Amerindian and Siberian populations have been used to argue for early isolation of [[Founder effect|founding populations]] on [[Beringia]]<ref name=Tammetal>{{cite journal |first1=Erika |last1=Tamm |first2=Toomas |last2=Kivisild |first3=Maere |last3=Reidla |first4=Mait |last4=Metspalu |first5=David Glenn |last5=Smith |first6=Connie J. |last6=Mulligan |first7=Claudio M. |last7=Bravi |first8=Olga |last8=Rickards |first9=Cristina |last9=Martinez-Labarga |first10=Elsa K. |last10=Khusnutdinova |first11=Sardana A. |last11=Fedorova |first12=Maria V. |last12=Golubenko |first13=Vadim A. |last13=Stepanov |first14=Marina A. |last14=Gubina |first15=Sergey I. |last15=Zhadanov |first16=Ludmila P. |last16=Ossipova  |first17=Larisa |last17=Damba |first18=Mikhail I. |last18=Voevoda |first19=Jose E. |last19=Dipierri |first20=Richard |last20=Villems
|first21=Ripan S. |last21=Malhi |display-authors=3 |title=Beringian Standstill and Spread of Native American Founders |volume=2 |issue=9 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0000829 |pmid=17786201 |pmc=1952074|date=5 September 2007|journal=[[PLoS One]] |pages=e829|bibcode=2007PLoSO...2..829T }}</ref> and for later, more rapid migration from [[Siberia]] through Beringia into the [[New World]].<ref name=Derenkoetal>{{cite journal |first1=Miroslava |last1=Derenko |first2=Boris |last2=Malyarchuk |first3=Tomasz |last3=Grzybowski |first4=Galina |last4=Denisova |first5=Urszula |last5=Rogalla |first6=Maria |last6=Perkova |first7=Irina |last7=Dambueva |first8=Ilia |last8=Zakharov |display-authors=3 |title=Origin and Post-Glacial Dispersal of Mitochondrial DNA Haplogroups C and D in Northern Asia |journal=PLOS ONE |volume= 5 |issue=12 |pages=e15214 |date=21 December 2010 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0015214 |pmid=21203537 |pmc=3006427 |bibcode=2010PLoSO...515214D }}</ref> The [[microsatellite]] diversity and distributions of the Y lineage specific to [[South America]] indicates that certain Amerindian populations have been isolated since the initial colonization of the region.<ref name=Bortolini>{{cite journal |first1=Maria-Catira |last1=Bortolini |first2=Francisco M. |last2=Salzano |first3=Mark G. |last3=Thomas |first4=Steven |last4=Stuart |first5=Selja P.K. |last5=Nasanen |first6=Claiton H.D. |last6=Bau |first7=Mara H. |last7=Hutz |first8=Zulay |last8=Layrisse |first9=Maria L. |last9=Petzl-Erler |first10=Luiza T. |last10=Tsuneto |first11=Kim |last11=Hill |first12=Ana M. |last12=Hurtado |first13=Dinorah |last13=Castro-de-Guerra |first14=Maria M. |last14=Torres |first15=Helena |last15=Groot |first16=Roman |last16=Michalski |first17=Pagbajabyn |last17=Nymadawa |first18=Gabriel |last18=Bedoya |first19=Neil |last19=Bradman |first20=Damian |last20=Labuda |first21=Andres |last21=Ruiz-Linares |display-authors=3 |title=Y-chromosome evidence for differing ancient demographic histories in the Americas |journal=[[American Journal of Human Genetics]] |volume=73 |issue=3 |date=September 2003 | pages=524–539 |pmc=1180678 |pmid=12900798 |doi=10.1086/377588 |url=http://www.cell.com/ajhg/pdf/S0002-9297(07)62016-3.pdf}}</ref> The [[Na-Dené]], [[Inuit]] and [[Alaska Natives|Indigenous Alaskan]] populations exhibit [[Haplogroup Q-M242]]; however, they are distinct from other indigenous Amerindians with various mtDNA and atDNA mutations.<ref name=NaDene/><ref name=Zegura/><ref name=inuit>{{cite journal |title=mtDNA Variation among Greenland Eskimos. The Edge of the Beringian Expansion |url=http://www.cell.com/ajhg/pdf/S0002-9297(07)63257-1.pdf |journal=American Journal of Human Genetics |first1=Juliette |last1=Saillard |first2=Peter |last2=Forster |first3=Niels |last3=Lynnerup |first4=Hans-Jürgen |last4=Bandelt |first5=Søren |last5=Nørby |volume=67 |pages=718–726 |year=2000 |doi=10.1086/303038 |issue=3 |pmid=10924403 |pmc=1287530}}</ref> This suggests that the peoples who first settled in the northern extremes of [[North America]] and [[Greenland]] derived from later migrant populations than those who penetrated farther south in the Americas.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schurr |first1=Theodore G. |title=The Peopling of the New World: Perspectives from Molecular Anthropology |journal=[[Annual Review of Anthropology]] |date=21 October 2004 |volume=33 |pages=551–583 |doi=10.1146/annurev.anthro.33.070203.143932}}</ref><ref name=Nadene1>{{cite journal |first1=Antonio |last1=Torroni |first2=Theodore  G. |last2=Schurr |first3=Chi-Chuan |last3=Yang |first4=Emoke J. E. |last4=Szathmary |first5=Robert C. |last5=Williams |first6=Moses S. |last6=Schanfield |first7=Gary A. |last7=Troup |first8=William C. |last8=Knowler |first9=Dale N. |last9=Lawrence |first10=Kenneth M. |last10=Weiss |first11=Douglas C. |last11=Wallace |display-authors=3 |title=Native American Mitochondrial DNA Analysis Indicates That the Amerind and the Nadene Populations Were Founded by Two Independent Migrations |journal=[[Genetics (journal)|Genetics]] |volume=30 |issue=1 |pages=153–162 |pmid=1346260 |url=http://www.genetics.org/content/genetics/130/1/153.full.pdf |pmc=1204788 |date=January 1992}}</ref> [[Linguists]] and [[biologist]]s have reached a similar conclusion based on analysis of [[Indigenous languages of the Americas|Amerindian language groups]] and [[ABO blood group system]] distributions.<ref>{{cite news |first=Nicholas |last=Wade |title=Pause Is Seen in a Continent’s Peopling |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/13/science/linguistic-study-sheds-new-light-on-peopling-of-north-america.html |date=12 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |chapter=Native Languages of the Americas |title=An Introduction to the Languages of the World
 |first=Anatole V. |last=Lyovin |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/?id=y6Y-L4ogfhIC&pg=PA309 |year=1997|publisher=Oxford University  |page=309 |isbn=978-0-19-508115-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Mithun |first=Marianne |title=Studies of North American Indian Languages |journal=Annual Review of Anthropology |volume=19 |issue=1 |pages=309–330 |date=October 1990 |doi=10.1146/annurev.an.19.100190.001521 |jstor=2155968}}</ref>

==Autosomal DNA==
{{details|topic=autosomal DNA in general|Human genetic variation}}
[[File:Genetic group American Native American DNA subrace.png|thumb|upright=1.4|<center>Genetic groups according to [[Tribal DNA]]</center>
{{refbegin|2}}
{{legend|#52F3FF|1. [[Alaska Natives|Arctic]]}}{{legend|#CA226B|2. [[Salishan languages|Salishan]]}}{{legend|#2554C7|3. [[Athabaskan languages|Athabaskan]]}}{{legend|#6AFB92|4. North Amerindian}}{{legend|yellow|5. [[Ojibwa]]}}{{legend|#D16587|6. [[Mexica]]}}{{legend|#6698FF|7. [[Maya peoples|Maya]]}}{{legend|#C38EC7|8. [[Chibchan languages|Chibcha]]}}{{legend|#667C26|9. [[Inca Empire|Andean]]}}{{legend|#387C44|10. [[Amazon Basin|Amazonian]]}}{{legend|#E8A317|11. [[Gran Chaco]]}}{{legend|#E41B17|12. [[Patagonian]]}}
{{refend}}]]
Genetic diversity and population structure in the American landmass is also measured using [[autosomal]] ([[atDNA]]) micro-satellite markers [[genotype]]d; sampled from North, Central, and South America and analyzed against similar data available from other [[Indigenous peoples|indigenous populations]] worldwide.<ref name=atdna>{{cite journal |first1=Sijia |last1=Wang |first2=Cecil M., Jr. |last2=Lewis |first3=Mattias |last3=Jakobsson |first4=Sohini |last4=Ramachandran |first5=Nicolas |last5=Ray |first6=Gabriel |last6=Bedoya |first7=Winston |last7=Rojas |first8=Maria V. |last8=Parra |first9=Julio A. |last9=Molina |first10=Carla |last10=Gallo |first11=Guido |last11=Mazzotti |first12=Giovanni |last12=Poletti |first13=Kim |last13=Hill |first14=Ana M. |last14=Hurtado |first15=Damian |last15=Labuda |first16=William |last16=Klitz |first17=Ramiro |last17=Barrantes |first18=Maria Cátira |last18=Bortolini |first19=Francisco M. |last19=Salzano |first20=Maria Luiza |last20=Petzl-Erler |first21=Luiza T. |last21=Tsuneto |first22=Elena |last22=Llop |first23=Francisco |last23=Rothhammer |first24=Laurent |last24=Excoffier |first25=Marcus W. |last25=Feldman |first26=Noah A. |last26=Rosenberg |first27=Andrés |last27=Ruiz-Linares |display-authors=3 |date=23 November 2007 |title=Genetic Variation and Population Structure in Native Americans |journal=PLoS Genetics |volume=3 |issue=11 |pages=e185 |pmc=2082466 |pmid=18039031 |doi=10.1371/journal.pgen.0030185}}</ref><ref name=jointm/> The Amerindian populations show a lower [[genetic diversity]] than populations from other continental regions.<ref name=jointm/> Observed is a decreasing genetic diversity as geographic distance from the Bering Strait occurs, as well as a decreasing genetic similarity to Siberian populations from Alaska (the genetic entry point).<ref name=atdna/><ref name=jointm>{{cite journal |first1=Bruce |last1=Walsh |first2=Alan |last2=Redd |first3=Michael F. |last3=Hammer |title=Joint match probabilities for Y chromosomal and autosomal markers |journal=Forensic Science International |volume=174 |issue=2–3 |pages=234–238 |url=http://nitro.biosci.arizona.edu/zdownload/papers/FSI-2008.PDF |date=30 January 2008 |pmid=17449208 |doi=10.1016/j.forsciint.2007.03.014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703045010/http://nitro.biosci.arizona.edu/zdownload/papers/FSI-2008.PDF |archivedate=2010-07-03}}</ref>
Also observed is evidence of a higher level of diversity and lower level of population structure in western South America compared to eastern South America.<ref name=atdna/><ref name=jointm/> There is a relative lack of differentiation between [[Mesoamerican]] and [[Andes|Andean]] populations, a scenario that implies that coastal routes were easier for migrating peoples (more genetic contributors) to traverse in comparison with inland routes.<ref name=atdna/>

The over-all pattern that is emerging suggests that the Americas were colonized by a small number of individuals (effective size of about 70), which grew by a factor of 10 over 800 – 1000 years.<ref name=SpencerWells2/><ref name=portrait/> The data also shows that there have been genetic exchanges between Asia, the Arctic, and Greenland since the initial peopling of the Americas.<ref name=portrait>{{cite journal |title=On the Number of New World Founders: A Population Genetic Portrait of the Peopling of the Americas|journal=Hey J: PLoS Biol |doi=10.1371/journal.pbio.0030193|year=2005  |volume=3 |issue=6|page=e193 |pmid=15898833 |pmc=1131883 | last1 = Hey | first1 = J}}</ref><ref name=genomes>{{cite news |title=Ancient Man In Greenland Has Genome Decoded |first=Nicholas |last=Wade |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/11/science/11genome.html |work=The New York Times |date=2010-02-11}}</ref>

Moreno-Mayar et al. (2018) have identified a basal '''Ancestral Native American''' (ANA) lineage.
This lineage formed by admixture of early [[East Asians|East Asian]] and [[Ancient North Eurasian]] lineages prior to the 
[[Last Glacial Maximum]], ca. 36&ndash;25 kya. Basal ANA diverged into an "[[Ancient Beringian]]" (AB) lineage at ca. 20 kya. 
The non-AB lineage further diverged into  "Northern Native American" (NNA) and "Southern Native American" (SNA) lineages between about 17.5 and 14.6 kya. Most pre-Columbian lineages are derived from NNA and SNA, except for the American Arctic, where there is evidence of later (after 10kya) admixture from [[Paleo-Siberian]] lineages.<ref name="Moreno-Mayar2018"/>

In 2014, the autosomal DNA of a 12,500+-year-old infant from Montana was sequenced.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The genome of a Late Pleistocene human from a Clovis burial site in western Montana |journal=Nature |volume=506 |issue=7487 |pages=225–229 |year=2014 |doi=10.1038/nature13025|pmid=24522598 |last1=Rasmussen |first1=Morten |last2=Anzick |first2=Sarah L. |last3=Waters |first3=Michael R. |last4=Skoglund |first4=Pontus |last5=Degiorgio |first5=Michael |last6=Stafford |first6=Thomas W. |last7=Rasmussen |first7=Simon |last8=Moltke |first8=Ida |last9=Albrechtsen |first9=Anders |last10=Doyle |first10=Shane M. |last11=Poznik |first11=G. David |last12=Gudmundsdottir |first12=Valborg |last13=Yadav |first13=Rachita |last14=Malaspinas |first14=Anna-Sapfo |last15=v |first15=Samuel Stockton White |last16=Allentoft |first16=Morten E. |last17=Cornejo |first17=Omar E. |last18=Tambets |first18=Kristiina |last19=Eriksson |first19=Anders |last20=Heintzman |first20=Peter D. |last21=Karmin |first21=Monika |last22=Korneliussen |first22=Thorfinn Sand |last23=Meltzer |first23=David J. |last24=Pierre |first24=Tracey L. |last25=Stenderup |first25=Jesper |last26=Saag |first26=Lauri |last27=Warmuth |first27=Vera M. |last28=Lopes |first28=Margarida C. |last29=Malhi |first29=Ripan S. |last30=Brunak |first30=Søren |display-authors=3|bibcode = 2014Natur.506..225R |pmc=4878442}}</ref> The DNA was taken from a skeleton referred to as Anzick-1, found in close association with several Clovis artifacts. Comparisons showed strong affinities with DNA from Siberian sites, and virtually ruled out that particular individual had any close affinity with European sources (the "[[Solutrean hypothesis]]"). The DNA also showed strong affinities with all existing Amerindian populations, which indicated that all of them derive from an ancient population that lived in or near Siberia, the Upper Palaeolithic [[Mal'ta]] population.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ancient American's genome mapped |publisher=BBC News |date=2014-02-14 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-26172174}}</ref>

According to an autosomal genetic study from 2012,<ref name="nature.com">{{cite journal|url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v488/n7411/abs/nature11258.html|title=Reconstructing Native American population history|accessdate=10 November 2015 | volume=488|issue=7411|doi=10.1038/nature11258|pmid=22801491|pmc=3615710|journal=Nature|pages=370–374|year=2012|last1=Reich|first1=David|last2=Patterson|first2=Nick|last3=Campbell|first3=Desmond|last4=Tandon|first4=Arti|last5=Mazieres|first5=Stéphane|last6=Ray|first6=Nicolas|last7=Parra|first7=Maria V|last8=Rojas|first8=Winston|last9=Duque|first9=Constanza|last10=Mesa|first10=Natalia|last11=García|first11=Luis F|last12=Triana|first12=Omar|last13=Blair|first13=Silvia|last14=Maestre|first14=Amanda|last15=Dib|first15=Juan C|last16=Bravi|first16=Claudio M|last17=Bailliet|first17=Graciela|last18=Corach|first18=Daniel|last19=Hünemeier|first19=Tábita|last20=Bortolini|first20=Maria Cátira|last21=Salzano|first21=Francisco M|last22=Petzl-Erler|first22=María Luiza|last23=Acuña-Alonzo|first23=Victor|last24=Aguilar-Salinas|first24=Carlos|last25=Canizales-Quinteros|first25=Samuel|last26=Tusié-Luna|first26=Teresa|last27=Riba|first27=Laura|last28=Rodríguez-Cruz|first28=Maricela|last29=Lopez-Alarcón|first29=Mardia|last30=Coral-Vazquez|first30=Ramón|display-authors=3|bibcode=2012Natur.488..370R}}</ref> Native Americans descend of at least three main migrant waves from East Asia. Most of it is traced back to a single ancestral population, called 'First Americans'. However, those who speak [[Inuit languages]] from the [[Arctic]] inherited almost half of their ancestry from a second East Asian migrant wave. And those who speak [[Na-dene]], on the other hand, inherited a tenth of their ancestry from a third migrant wave. The initial settling of the Americas was followed by a rapid expansion southwards, by the coast, with little gene flow later, especially in [[South America]]. One exception to this are the [[Chibcha]] speakers, whose ancestry comes from both North and South America.
<ref name="nature.com"/>

Linguistic studies have backed up genetic studies, with ancient patterns having been found between the languages spoken in [[Siberia]] and those spoken in the Americas.{{clarify|date=July 2018}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=Abstract Profiles of Structural Stability Point to Universal Tendencies, Family-Specific Factors, and Ancient Connections between Languages|first1=Dan|last1=Dediu|first2=Stephen C.|last2=Levinson|date=20 September 2012|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=7|issue=9|pages=e45198|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0045198|pmid=23028843|bibcode=2012PLoSO...745198D|pmc=3447929}}</ref>

Two 2015 autosomal DNA genetic studies confirmed the Siberian origins of the Natives of the Americas. However an ancient signal of shared ancestry with Australasians (Natives of Australia, Melanesia and the Andaman Islands) was detected among the Natives of the [[Amazon region]]. The migration coming out of [[Siberia]] would have happened 23,000 years ago.<ref>{{Cite journal |url=https://www.sciencemag.org/content/349/6250/aab3884.abstract|title=Genomic evidence for the Pleistocene and recent population history of Native Americans|journal=Science|volume=349|issue=6250|pages=aab3884| author=Raghavan |format=pdf |date=21 August 2015|access-date=6 October 2015 |quote= |display-authors=etal|doi=10.1126/science.aab3884|pmid=26198033|pmc=4733658}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url= http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v525/n7567/full/nature14895.html |title=Genetic evidence for two founding populations of the Americas|format=pdf |date=21 July 2015|access-date=7 October 2015 |doi=10.1038/nature14895 |volume=525 |issue=7567|journal=Nature |pmid=26196601 |pmc=4982469 |pages=104–8 | last1 = Skoglund | first1 = P | last2 = Mallick | first2 = S | last3 = Bortolini | first3 = MC | last4 = Chennagiri | first4 = N | last5 = Hünemeier | first5 = T | last6 = Petzl-Erler | first6 = ML | last7 = Salzano | first7 = FM | last8 = Patterson | first8 = N | last9 = Reich | first9 = D |display-authors=3 |bibcode=2015Natur.525..104S}}</ref><ref name="Skoglund2016">{{cite journal|last1= Skoglund|first1= P.|last2= Reich|first2= D.|title=A genomic view of the peopling of the Americas|journal= Current Opinion in Genetics & Development|volume= 41|year= 2016|pages= 27–35|doi= 10.1016/j.gde.2016.06.016|pmid= 27507099|pmc= 5161672}}</ref>

==Paternal lineages==
{{details|topic=individual Amerindian groups by Y-DNA|Y-DNA haplogroups in indigenous peoples of the Americas}}

A "Central Siberian" origin has been postulated for the paternal lineage of the source populations of the original migration into the Americas.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Santos |first1=Fabrício  R. |last2=Pandya |first2=Arpita |last3=Tyler-Smith |first3=Chris |last4=Pena |first4=Sérgio D.J. |last5=Schanfield |first5=Moses |last6=Leonard |first6=William R. |last7=Osipova |first7=Ludmila  |last8=Crawford |first8=Michael H. |last9=Mitchell | first9=R. John|display-authors=3 |date=February 1999 |title=The Central Siberian Origin for Native American Y Chromosomes
 |journal=American Journal of Human Genetics |volume=64 |issue=2 |pages=619–628 |pmc=1377773 |pmid=9973301 |doi=10.1086/302242}}</ref>

Membership in haplogroups [[Haplogroup Q (Y-DNA)|Q]] and [[Haplogroup C3 (Y-DNA)|C3b]] implies indigenous American patrilineal descent.<ref name="José">{{cite book|author1=Blanco Verea |author2=Alejandro José |title=Linajes del cromosoma Y humano: aplicaciones genético-poblacionales y forenses |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1KEFL5gSznUC&pg=PA135 |accessdate=2011-06-15 |publisher=Univ Santiago de Compostela|pages=135–|id=GGKEY:JCW0ASCR364}}</ref>

===Haplogroup Q===
{{details|Haplogroup Q-M242 (Y-DNA)}}
[[File:Haplogroup Q (Y-DNA).PNG|thumb|upright=1.6|Spread of Haplogroup Q in indigenous populations.]]
[[Haplogroup Q (Y-DNA)|Q-M242]] (mutational name) is the defining (SNP) of [[Haplogroup Q (Y-DNA)]] (phylogenetic name). Within the Q clade, there are 14 haplogroups marked by 17 SNPs.<sup>2009</sup><ref name=how>{{cite web|title=How the Subclades of Y-DNA Haplogroup Q are determined|url=http://www.genebase.com/store/product.php?spId=50|publisher=Genebase Systems|year=2009|accessdate=2009-11-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100121013034/http://www.genebase.com/store/product.php?spId=50#|archive-date=2010-01-21|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref><ref name=Tree>{{cite web|title=Y-DNA Haplogroup Tree|url=http://www.genebase.com/resource/phylogeneticTree.php?hap=K|publisher=Genebase Systems|year=2009|accessdate=2009-11-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225030411/http://www.genebase.com/resource/phylogeneticTree.php?hap=K#|archive-date=2010-12-25|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> In [[Eurasia]], haplogroup Q is found among indigenous [[Indigenous peoples of Siberia|Siberian populations]], such as the modern [[Chukchi people|Chukchi]] and [[Koryaks|Koryak]] peoples. In particular, two groups exhibit large concentrations of the Q-M242 mutation, the [[Ket people|Ket]] (93.8%) and the [[Selkup people|Selkup]] (66.4%) peoples.<ref name=Distribution/> The Ket are thought to be the only survivors of [[Hunter-gatherer|ancient wanderers]] living in Siberia.<ref name=SpencerWells2/> Their population size is very small; there are fewer than 1,500 Ket in [[Russia]].<sup>2002</sup><ref name=SpencerWells2/> The Selkup have a slightly larger population size than the Ket, with approximately 4,250 individuals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.genebase.com/learning/article/16 |title=Learning Center :: Genebase Tutorials |publisher=Genebase.com |date=1964-10-22 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131117011216/http://www.genebase.com/learning/article/16 |archivedate=17 November 2013}}</ref>

Starting the [[Paleo-Indians|Paleo-Indians period]], a [[Prehistoric migration and settlement of the Americas from Asia|migration to the Americas]] across the [[Bering Strait]] ([[Beringia]]) by a small population carrying the Q-M242 mutation took place.<ref name=Zegura>{{cite journal |last1=Zegura |first1=Stephen L. |last2=Karafet |first2=Tatiana M. |last3=Zhivotovsky |first3=Lev A. |last4=Hammer |first4=Michael F. |title=High-Resolution SNPs and Microsatellite Haplotypes Point to a Single, Recent Entry of Native American Y Chromosomes into the Americas
 |journal=[[Molecular Biology and Evolution]] |volume=21 |issue=1 |pages=164–175 |date=January 2004 |pmid=14595095 |doi=10.1093/molbev/msh009 |url=https://academic.oup.com/mbe/article/21/1/164/1114763}}</ref> A member of this initial population underwent a mutation, which defines its descendant population, known by the [[Haplogroup Q1a3a (Y-DNA)|Q-M3]] (SNP) mutation.<ref>{{cite journal |title=A single and early migration for the peopling of the Americas supported by mitochondrial DNA sequence data |pmc=20009 |date=4 March 1997 | pmid=9050871 |last1=Bonatto |first1=SL |last2=Salzano |first2=FM |volume=94 |issue=5 |pages=1866–1871 |journal=[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America]] |doi=10.1073/pnas.94.5.1866 |bibcode = 1997PNAS...94.1866B}}</ref> These descendants migrated all over the Americas.<ref name=how/>

[[Haplogroup Q-M3]] is defined by the presence of the rs3894 (M3) (SNP).<ref name=Genebase>{{cite web|title=Learn about Y-DNA Haplogroup Q. Genebase Tutorials |author=Wendy Tymchuk, Senior Technical Editor |url=http://www.genebase.com/tutorial/item.php?tuId=16 |publisher=Genebase Systems |year=2008 |accessdate=2009-11-21 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100622001311/http://www.genebase.com/tutorial/item.php?tuId=16 |archivedate=2010-06-22 |df= }}</ref><ref name=SpencerWells2>{{cite book|last=Wells|first=Spencer|title=The Journey of Man: A Genetic Odyssey|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WAsKm-_zu5sC&pg=PA138|year=2002|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-11532-0|pages=138–140}}</ref><ref name="SmolenyakTurner2004">{{cite book|last1=Smolenyak|first1=Megan|last2=Turner|first2=Ann|title=Trace Your Roots with DNA: Using Genetic Tests to Explore Your Family Tree|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J9evrYLpDVEC&pg=PA83|year=2004|publisher=Rodale|isbn=978-1-59486-006-5 |page=83}}</ref> The Q-M3 mutation is roughly 15,000 years old as that is when the initial migration of Paleo-Indians into the Americas occurred.<ref name=first2>{{cite news |title=New World Settlers Took 20,000-Year Pit Stop |first=Ker |last=Than |url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2008/02/080214-america-layover.html |work=National Geographic News |date=14 February 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=First Americans Arrived Recently, Settled Pacific Coast, DNA Study Says |url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2007/02/070202-human-migration.html |work=National Geographic News |first=Stefan |last=Lovgren |date=2 February 2007}}</ref> Q-M3 is the predominant haplotype in the Americas, at a rate of 83% in South American populations,<ref name=Bortolini/> 50% in the Na-Dené populations, and in North American Eskimo-Aleut populations at about 46%.<ref name=Distribution>{{cite web|title=Frequency Distribution of Y-DNA Haplogroup Q1a3a-M3|url=http://www.genetree.com/education/q|publisher=GeneTree|year=2010|accessdate=2010-01-30|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091104070218/http://www.genetree.com/education/q|archivedate=2009-11-04|df=}}</ref> With minimal back-migration of Q-M3 in Eurasia, the mutation likely evolved in east-Beringia, or more specifically the [[Seward Peninsula]] or [[Alaska Interior|western Alaskan interior]]. The Beringia land mass began submerging, cutting off land routes.<ref name=Distribution/><ref name=First>{{cite web|title=First Americans Endured 20,000-Year Layover – Jennifer Viegas, Discovery News |url=http://dsc.discovery.com/news/2008/02/13/beringia-native-american.html |accessdate=2009-11-18 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010092348/http://dsc.discovery.com/news/2008/02/13/beringia-native-american.html |archivedate=2012-10-10 |df= |date=2017-05-10 }} [http://dsc.discovery.com/news/2008/02/13/beringia-native-american-02.html page 2] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313061401/http://dsc.discovery.com/news/2008/02/13/beringia-native-american-02.html |date=March 13, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=atdna/>

[[File:Density and frequency haplogroup R.jpg|thumb|upright=1.6|Y chromosome R haplogroup among Native Americans (right; Malhi et al., 2008), and population density mapping (left) indicate a non-correlation between haplogroup R frequency and population density. The study of Malhi et al. 2008 suggest European admixture has resulted in a decreasing gradient of haplogroup R in Native Americans.<ref name=Athapaskan>{{cite journal |first1=Ripan Singh |last1=Malhi |first2=Angelica |last2=Gonzalez-Oliver |first3=Kari Britt |last3=Schroeder |first4=Brian M. |last4=Kemp |first5=Jonathan A. |last5=Greenberg |first6=Solomon Z. |last6=Dobrowski |first7=David Glenn |last7=Smith |first8=Andres |last8=Resendez |first9=Tatiana |last9=Karafet |first10=Michael |last10=Hammer |first11=Stephen |last11=Zegura |first12=Tatiana |last12=Brovko |display-authors=3 |date=10 July 2008 |title=Distribution of Y Chromosomes Among Native North Americans: A Study of Athapaskan Population History | url = | journal = [[American Journal of Physical Anthropology]] |volume=137 |issue=4 |pages=412–424 |pmid=18618732 |doi=10.1002/ajpa.20883 |pmc=2584155}}</ref>]]

Since the discovery of Q-M3, several [[subclade]]s of M3-bearing populations have been discovered. An example is in [[South America]], where some populations have a high prevalence of (SNP) M19 which defines subclade '''Q-M19'''.<ref name=Bortolini/> M19 has been detected in (59%) of Amazonian [[Ticuna people|Ticuna]] men and in (10%) of [[Wayuu people|Wayuu]] men.<ref name=Bortolini/> Subclade M19 appears to be unique to [[South American Indigenous people]]s, arising 5,000 to 10,000 years ago.<ref name=Bortolini/> This suggests that population isolation and perhaps even the establishment of tribal groups began soon after migration into the South American areas.<ref name=SpencerWells2/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=González Burchard |first1=Esteban  |last2=Borrell |first2=Luisa N. |last3=Choudhry |first3=Shweta  |last4=Naqvi |first4=Mariam  |last5=Tsai |first5=Hui-Ju |last6=Rodriguez-Santana |first6=Jose R. |last7=Chapela |first7=Rocio  |last8=Rogers |first8=Scott D. |last9=Mei |first9=Rui 
|first10=William |last10=Rodriguez-Cintron |first11=Jose F. |last11=Arena |first12=Rick |last12=Kittles |first13=Eliseo J. |last13=Perez-Stable |first14=Elad |last14=Ziv |first15=Neil |last15=Risch |display-authors=3

|title=Latino Populations: A Unique Opportunity for the Study of Race, Genetics, and Social Environment in Epidemiological Research |journal=[[American Journal of Public Health]] |date=December 2005 |volume=95 |pmid=16257940 |number=12 |pmc=1449501 |pages=2161–2168 |doi=10.2105/AJPH.2005.068668}}</ref> Other American subclades include [[Haplogroup Q-L54 (Y-DNA)|Q-L54]], [[Haplogroup Q-Z780 (Y-DNA)|Q-Z780]], [[Haplogroup Q-MEH2 (Y-DNA)|Q-MEH2]], [[Haplogroup Q-SA01 (Y-DNA)|Q-SA01]], and [[Haplogroup Q-M346 (Y-DNA)|Q-M346]] lineages. In Canada, two other lineages have been found. These are [[Haplogroup Q-P89.1 (Y-DNA)|Q-P89.1]] and [[Haplogroup Q-NWT01 (Y-DNA)|Q-NWT01]].

The principal-component analysis suggests a close genetic relatedness between some North American Amerindians (the Chipewyan and the Cheyenne) and certain populations of central/southern Siberia (particularly the Kets, Yakuts, Selkups and Altays), at the resolution of major Y-chromosome haplogroups.<ref name=Bortolini/> This pattern agrees with the distribution of [[Haplogroup X (mtDNA)|mtDNA haplogroup X]], which is found in North America, is absent from eastern Siberia, but is present in the Altais of southern central Siberia. Similarly, the Asian populations closest to Native Americans are characterized by a predominance of lineage P-M45* and low frequencies of C-RPS4Y.<ref name=Bortolini/>

===Haplogroup R1===
{{details|Haplogroup R1 (Y-DNA)}}
{{details|Mal'ta-Buret' culture#Relationship to American Indians and Europeans}}

[[File:Haplogroup R (Y-DNA).PNG|thumb|upright=1.6|Spread of Haplogroup R in Indigenous populations.]] 
[[Haplogroup R1 (Y-DNA)]] (specifically [[Haplogroup R1b (Y-DNA)|R1b]]) is the second most predominant Y haplotype found among indigenous Amerindians after Q (Y-DNA).<ref name=Athapaskan/> The distribution of R1 is believed by some to be associated with the re-settlement of Eurasia following the [[Wisconsin glaciation|last glacial maximum]]. One theory put forth is that R1 entered the Americas with the initial founding population,<ref name=Bortolini/> suggesting prehistoric Amerindian immigration from Asia through Beringia<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Lell | first1 = Jeffrey T. | last2 = Sukernik | first2 = Rem I. | last3 = Starikovskaya | first3 = Yelena B. | last4 = Su | first4 = Bing | last5 = Jin | first5 = Li | last6 = Schurr | first6 = Theodore G. | last7 = Underhill | first7 = Peter A. | last8 = Wallace | first8 = Douglas C. |display-authors=3 | year = 2002 | title = The Dual Origin and Siberian Affinities of Native American | url = | journal = The American Journal of Human Genetics | volume = 70 | issue = 1| pages = 192–206 | doi=10.1086/338457 | pmid=11731934 | pmc=384887}}</ref><ref name="renamed_from_24256729_on_20160803111353">{{cite journal | last1 = Raghavan | first1 = Maanasa | last2 = Skoglund | first2 = Pontus | last3 = Graf | first3 = Kelly E. | last4 = Metspalu | first4 = Mait | last5 = Albrechtsen | first5 = Anders | last6 = Moltke | first6 = Ida | last7 = Rasmussen | first7 = Simon | last8 = Thomas | first8 = W. Stafford Jr | last9 = Orlando | first9 = Ludovic | last10 = Metspalu | first10 = Ene | last11 = Karmin | first11 = Monika | last12 = Tambets | first12 = Kristiina | last13 = Rootsi | first13 = Siiri | last14 = Mägi | first14 = Reedik | last15 = Campos | first15 = Paula F. | last16 = Balanovska | first16 = Elena | last17 = Balanovsky | first17 = Oleg | last18 = Khusnutdinova | first18 = Elza | last19 = Litvinov | first19 = Sergey | last20 = Osipova | first20 = Ludmila P. | last21 = Fedorova | first21 = Sardana A. | last22 = Voevoda | first22 = Mikhail I. | last23 = DeGiorgio | first23 = Michael | last24 = Sicheritz-Ponten | first24 = Thomas | last25 = Brunak | first25 = Søren | display-authors = 3 | last26 = et al | year = 2014 | title = Upper Palaeolithic Siberian genome reveals dual ancestry of Native Americans | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 505 | issue = 7481| pages = 87–91 | doi=10.1038/nature12736 | pmid=24256729 | pmc=4105016| bibcode = 2014Natur.505...87R }}</ref> and correlating mostly with the frequency of haplogroups Q-M3 and P-M45*.<ref name=Bortolini/> A second  theory is that it was introduced during European colonization.<ref name=Athapaskan/> R1 is very common throughout all of Eurasia except [[East Asia]] and [[Southeast Asia]]. '''R1 (M173)''' is found predominantly in North American groups like the [[Ojibwe]] (50-79%), [[Seminole]] (50%), [[Sioux]] (50%), [[Cherokee]] (47%), [[Dogrib people|Dogrib]] (40%) and [[Tohono O'odham]] (Papago) (38%).<ref name=Athapaskan/>

A study of Raghavan et al. 2013 found that autosomal evidence indicates that skeletal remain of a south-central Siberian child carrying [[Haplogroup R-M207|R* y-dna]] ([[Mal'ta-Buret' culture|Mal'ta boy-1]]) "is basal to modern-day western Eurasians and genetically closely related to modern-day Amerindians, with no close affinity to east Asians. This suggests that populations related to contemporary western Eurasians had a more north-easterly distribution 24,000 years ago than commonly thought." Sequencing of another south-central Siberian ([[Afontova Gora|Afontova Gora-2]]) revealed that "western Eurasian genetic signatures in modern-day Amerindians derive not only from post-Columbian admixture, as commonly thought, but also from a mixed ancestry of the First Americans."<ref name="renamed_from_24256729_on_20160803111353"/> It is further theorized if "Mal'ta might be a missing link, a representative of the Asian population that admixed both into Europeans and Native Americans."<ref>{{cite journal |author=Michael Balter |title=Ancient DNA Links Native Americans With Europe |journal=Science |volume=342 |issue=6157 |pages=409–410 |date=October 2013  |doi=10.1126/science.342.6157.409 |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/content/342/6157/409.full|bibcode = 2013Sci...342..409B |pmid=24159019}}</ref>

===Haplogroup C-P39===
{{details|Haplogroup C-M217 (Y-DNA)}}
[[File:Distribution of Haplogroup C-M217 Y-DNA - worldwide.png|thumb|upright=1.6|Spread of Haplogroup C-M217 in Indigenous populations.]]
Haplogroup C-M217 is mainly found in indigenous Siberians, [[Mongols|Mongolians]] and [[Kazakhs]]. Haplogroup C-M217 is the most widespread and frequently occurring branch of the greater [[Haplogroup C-M130 (Y-DNA)|(Y-DNA) haplogroup C-M130]]. Haplogroup C-M217 descendant '''C-P39''' is commonly found in today's [[Na-Dene languages|Na-Dené speakers]], with the highest frequency found among the [[Athabaskan languages|Athabaskans]] at 42%.<ref name=Zegura/> This distinct and isolated branch '''C-P39''' includes almost all the Haplogroup C-M217 Y-chromosomes found among all indigenous peoples of the Americas.<ref name = "Xue2006">{{cite journal  |first1=Yali |last1=Xue |first2=Tatiana |last2=Zerjal |first3=Weidong |last3=Bao |first4=Suling |last4=Zhu |first5=Qunfang |last5=Shu |first6=Jiujin |last6=Xu |first7=Ruofu |last7=Du |first8=Songbin |last8=Fu |first9=Pu |last9=Li |first10=Matthew E. |last10=Hurles |first11=Huanming |last11=Yang |first12=Chris |last12=Tyler-Smith |display-authors=3 |title=Male Demography in East Asia: a North-South Contrast in Human Population Expansion Times |journal=Genetics |volume=172 |issue=4 |pages=2431–2439 |date=1 April 2006 |pmid=16489223 |pmc=1456369 |doi=10.1534/genetics.105.054270}}</ref> The Na-Dené groups are also unusual among indigenous peoples of the Americas in having a relatively high frequency of Q-M242 (25%).<ref name=Distribution/>

Some researchers feel that this may indicate that the Na-Dené migration occurred from the [[Russian Far East]] after the initial Paleo-Indian colonization, but prior to modern [[Inuit]], [[Inupiat]] and [[Yupik peoples|Yupik]] expansions.<ref name=Zegura/><ref name=NaDene>{{cite journal |doi=10.1073/pnas.95.23.13994 |last=Ruhlen |first=Merritt |title=The origin of the Na-Dene |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America |volume=95 |issue=23 |pages=13994–13996 |date=November 1998 |pmid=9811914 |pmc=25007 |url=http://www.pnas.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=9811914 |bibcode=1998PNAS...9513994R}}</ref><ref name="JOHANSENPRITZKER20077">{{cite encyclopedia |first=Aliki |last=Marinakis |title=Na-Dene People  |editor-last1=Johansen |editor-first1=Bruce E. |editor-last2=Pritzker |editor-first2=Barry M. |work=Encyclopedia of American Indian History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sGKL6E9_J6IC&pg=PA441 |date=2008 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |isbn=978-1-85109-818-7 |page=441}}</ref>

==Maternal lineages==
{{details|topic=mtDNA in general|Mitochondrial DNA}}
[[File:Map of gene flow in and out of Beringia.jpg|left|thumb|upright=1.25|Schematic illustration of maternal (mtDNA) gene-flow in and out of Beringia, from 25,000 years ago to present.|alt=Schematic illustration of maternal geneflow in and out of Beringia. Colours of the arrows correspond to approximate timing of the events and are decoded in the coloured time-bar. The initial peopling of Berinigia (depicted in light yellow) was followed by a standstill. After this, the ancestors of indigenous Americans spread swiftly all over the New World while some of the Beringian maternal lineages–C1a-spread westwards. More recent (shown in green) genetic exchange is manifested by back-migration of A2a into Siberia, and the spread of D2a into north-eastern America that post-dated the initial peopling of the New World.]]

The common occurrence of the mtDNA Haplogroups A, B, C, and D among eastern Asian and  Amerindian populations has long been recognized, along with the presence of Haplogroup X.<ref name=Schurr2000>{{cite journal |url=http://www.sas.upenn.edu/~tgschurr/pdf/Am%20Sci%20Article%202000.pdf |last=Schurr |first=Theodore G. |title=Mitochondrial DNA and the Peopling of the New World |journal=American Scientist Online |date=May–June 2000 }}</ref>  As a whole, the greatest frequency of the four Amerindian associated haplogroups occurs in the [[Altai Mountains|Altai]]-[[Baikal]] region of southern Siberia.<ref name=Zakharovetal2004>{{cite journal
|last1=Zakharov |first1=Ilia A. |last2=Derenko |first2=Miroslava V. |last3=Maliarchuk |first3=Boris A. |last4=Dambueva |first4=Irina K. |last5=Dorzhu |first5=Choduraa M. |last6=Rychkov |first6=Sergey Y. |display-authors=3 |title=Mitochondrial DNA variation in the aboriginal populations of the Altai-Baikal region: implications for the genetic history of North Asia and America |volume=1011 |issue=1 |pmid=15126280 |date=April 2004 |journal=Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences |pages=21–35 |doi=10.1196/annals.1293.003 |bibcode=2004NYASA1011...21Z}}</ref> Some subclades of C and D closer to the Amerindian subclades occur among Mongolian, Amur, Japanese, Korean, and Ainu populations.<ref name=Schurr2000 /><ref name=Starikovskayaetal2005>{{cite journal |last1=Starikovskaya |first1=Elena B. |last2=Sukernik |first2=Rem I. |last3=Derbeneva |first3=Olga A. |last4=Volodko |first4=Natalia A. |last5=Ruiz-Pesini |first5=Eduardo |last6=Torroni |first6=Antonio |last7=Brown |first7=Michael D. |last8=Lott |first8=Marie T. |last9=Hosseini |first9=Seyed H. |last10=Huoponen |first10=Kirsi |last11=Wallace |first11=Douglas C. |display-authors=3 |title=Mitochondrial DNA diversity in indigenous populations of the southern extent of Siberia, and the origins of Native American haplogroups |volume=69 |issue=1 |pmc=3905771 |pmid=15638829 |doi=10.1046/j.1529-8817.2003.00127.x |date=7 January 2005 |journal=Annals of Human Genetics |pages=67–89}}</ref>

When studying [[human mitochondrial DNA haplogroup|human mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) haplogroups]], the results indicated until recently{{year needed|date=July 2018}} that Indigenous Amerindian haplogroups, including [[Haplogroup X (mtDNA)|haplogroup X]], are part of a single founding East Asian population. It also indicates that the distribution of mtDNA haplogroups and the levels of sequence divergence among [[Indigenous languages of the Americas|linguistically similar groups]] were the result of multiple preceding migrations from [[Bering Strait]]s populations.<ref name=Founding>{{cite news |title=Native American DNA Links to Six "Founding Mothers" |first=Malcolm |last=Ritter |url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2008/03/080313-AP-native-amer.html |work=National Geographic News |date=13 March 2008 |agency=Associated Press}}{{unreliable source?|date=July 2018}}<!--don't cite journalism if you can cite the publication the journalistic report is based on! journalists get the details wrong 99% of the time.--></ref><ref name=Illinois/> 
All indigenous Amerindian mtDNA can be traced back to five haplogroups, [[Haplogroup A (mtDNA)|A]], [[Haplogroup B (mtDNA)|B]], [[Haplogroup C (mtDNA)|C]], [[Haplogroup D (mtDNA)|D]] and [[Haplogroup X (mtDNA)|X]].<ref name=types>{{cite journal |title= The Phylogeny of the Four Pan-American MtDNA Haplogroups: Implications for Evolutionary and Disease Studies |first1=Alessandro |last1=Achilli |first2=Ugo A. |last2=Perego |first3=Claudio M. |last3=Bravi |first4=Michael D. |last4=Coble |first5=Qing-Peng |last5=Kong |first6=Scott R. |last6=Woodward |first7=Antonio |last7=Salas |first8=Antonio |last8=Torroni |first9=Hans-Jürgen |last9=Bandelt |display-authors=3 |date=12 March 2008 |journal=PLoS ONE |volume=3 |pmid= 18335039 |issue=3 |pmc= 2258150 |pages=e1764 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0001764 |bibcode = 2008PLoSO...3.1764A}}</ref><ref name="Jablonski2002">{{cite book|author=Nina G. Jablonski|title=The first Americans: the Pleistocene colonization of the New World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RI32r548fUwC&pg=PA301 |accessdate=2011-06-15 |year=2002|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-940228-50-4|page=301}}</ref>
More specifically, indigenous Amerindian mtDNA belongs to sub-haplogroups A2, B2, C1b, C1c, C1d, D1, and X2a (with minor groups C4c, D2a, and D4h3a).<ref name=Tammetal /><ref name=Illinois>{{cite journal |first1=Jason A. |last1=Eshleman |first2=Ripan S. |last2=Malhi |first3=David Glenn |last3=Smith |title=Mitochondrial DNA Studies of Native Americans- Conceptions and Misconceptions of the Population Prehistory of the Americas |journal=[[Evolutionary Anthropology (journal)|Evolutionary Anthropology]] |date=14 February 2003 |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=7–18 |doi=10.1002/evan.10048}}</ref> 
This suggests that 95% of Indigenous Amerindian mtDNA is descended from a minimal genetic founding female population, comprising sub-haplogroups A2, B2, C1b, C1c, C1d, and D1.<ref name=types/> The remaining 5% is composed of the X2a, D2a, C4c, and D4h3a sub-haplogroups.<ref name=Illinois/><ref name=types/>

X is one of the five mtDNA haplogroups found in Indigenous Amerindian peoples. Unlike the four main American mtDNA haplogroups (A, B, C and D), X is not at all strongly associated with east Asia.<ref name=SpencerWells2/> Haplogroup X genetic sequences diverged about 20,000 to 30,000 years ago to give two sub-groups, X1 and X2. X2's subclade X2a occurs only at a frequency of about 3% for the total current indigenous population of the Americas.<ref name=SpencerWells2/> However, X2a is a major mtDNA subclade in North America; among the [[Algonquian peoples]], it comprises up to 25% of mtDNA types.<ref name=Genebase/><ref name="mma">{{cite web |url=http://www.physorg.com/news169474130.html |title=The peopling of the Americas: Genetic ancestry influences health |work=Scientific American |date=14 August 2009 |via=Phys.org}}</ref> It is also present in lower percentages to the west and south of this area — among the [[Sioux]] (15%), the [[Nuu-chah-nulth people|Nuu-chah-nulth]] (11%–13%), the [[Navajo people|Navajo]] (7%), and the [[Yakama]] (5%).<ref name=Fagundes>{{cite journal |last1=Fagundes |first1=Nelson J.R. |first2=Ricardo |last2=Kanitz |first3=Roberta |last3=Eckert |first4=Ana C.S. |last4=Valls |first5=Mauricio R. |last5=Bogo |first6=Francisco M. |last6=Salzano |first7=David Glenn |last7=Smith |first8=Wilson A. |last8=Silva |first9=Marco A. |last9=Zago |first10=Andrea K. |last10=Ribeiro-dos-Santos |first11=Sidney E.B. |last11=Santos |first12=Maria Luiza |last12=Petzl-Erler |first13=Sandro L. |last13=Bonatto |display-authors=3  |title=Mitochondrial Population Genomics Supports a Single Pre-Clovis Origin with a Coastal Route for the Peopling of the Americas |journal=American Journal of Human Genetics |volume=82 |issue=3 |date=3 March 2008 |pages=583–592 |pmid= 18313026 |pmc= 2427228 |doi=10.1016/j.ajhg.2007.11.013}}</ref> Haplogroup X is more strongly present in the [[Near East]], the [[Caucasus (geographic region)|Caucasus]], and [[Mediterranean Europe]].<ref name=Fagundes/> The predominant theory for sub-haplogroup X2a's appearance in North America is migration along with A, B, C, and D mtDNA groups, from a source in the [[Altai Mountains]] of central Asia.<ref name="Meltzer200909">{{cite book |first=David J. |last=Meltzer |title=First Peoples in a New World: Colonizing Ice Age America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Rnc-bg2voI8C&pg=PA162|year=2009|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-94315-5|page=162}}</ref><ref name=Cambridge>{{cite web|title=An mtDNA view of the peopling of the world by Homo sapiens |publisher=Cambridge DNA |url=https://www.cambridgedna.com/genealogy-dna-ancient-migrations-slideshow.php?view=step7 |year=2009 |accessdate=2010-04-29 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511091253/https://www.cambridgedna.com/genealogy-dna-ancient-migrations-slideshow.php?view=step7 |archivedate=2011-05-11}}</ref><ref name=haplox>{{cite journal |title=Origin and Diffusion of mtDNA Haplogroup X |year=November 2003 |pmc=1180497 |journal=American Journal of Human Genetics |volume=73 |issue=5 |pages=1178–1190 |pmid=14574647 |doi=10.1086/379380 |last1=Reidla |first1=Maere |last2=Kivisild |first2=Toomas |last3=Metspalu |first3=Ene |last4=Kaldma |first4=Katrin |last5=Tambets |first5=Kristiina |last6=Tolk |first6=Helle-Viivi |last7=Parik |first7=Jüri |last8=Loogväli |first8=Eva-Liis |last9=Derenko |first9=Miroslava |last10=Malyarchuk |first10=Boris |last11=Bermisheva |first11=Marina |last12=Zhadanov |first12=Sergey |last13=Pennarun |first13=Erwan |last14=Gubina |first14=Marina |last15=Golubenko |first15=Maria |last16=Damba |first16=Larisa |last17=Fedorova |first17=Sardana |last18=Gusar |first18=Vladislava |last19=Grechanina |first19=Elena |last20=Mikerezi |first20=Ilia |last21=Moisan |first21=Jean-Paul |last22=Chaventré |first22=André |last23=Khusnutdinova |first23=Elsa |last24=Osipova |first24=Ludmila |last25=Stepanov |first25=Vadim |last26=Voevoda |first26=Mikhail |last27=Achilli |first27=Alessandro |last28=Rengo |first28=Chiara |last29=Rickards |first29=Olga |last30=De Stefano |first30=Gian Franco |first31=Surinder |last31=Papiha |first32=Lars |last32=Beckman |first33=Branka |last33=Janicijevic |first34=Pavao |last34=Rudan |first35=Nicholas |last35=Anagnou |first36=Emmanuel |last36=Michalodimitrakis |first37=Slawomir |last37=Koziel |first38=Esien |last38=Usanga |first39=Tarekegn |last39=Geberhiwot |first40=Corinna |last40=Herrnstadt |first41=Neil |last41=Howell |first42=Antonio |last42=Torroni |first43=Richard |last43=Villems |display-authors=3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cambridgedna.com/genealogy-dna-ancient-migrations-slideshow.php?view=step7 |title=An mtDNA view of the peopling of the world by Homo sapiens |publisher=Cambridge DNA Services |year=2007 |accessdate=2011-06-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511091253/https://www.cambridgedna.com/genealogy-dna-ancient-migrations-slideshow.php?view=step7 |archivedate=2011-05-11 |df= }}</ref>

Sequencing of the mitochondrial genome from [[Paleo-Eskimo]] remains (3,500 years old) are distinct from modern Amerindians, falling within sub-haplogroup D2a1, a group observed among today's [[Aleutian Islands|Aleutian Islanders]], the [[Aleut]] and [[Siberian Yupik]] populations.<ref name=Eskimos/> This suggests that the colonizers of the far north, and subsequently Greenland, originated from later coastal populations.<ref name=Eskimos>{{cite journal |title=The St. Lawrence Island Eskimos, Genetic Variation and Genetic Distance |author1=Robert E. Ferrell |author2=Ranajit Chakraborty |author3=Henry Gershowitz |author4=W. S. Laughlin |author5=W. J. Schull |url=http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/journal/110483223/abstract |journal=American Journal of Physical Anthropology |doi=10.1002/ajpa.1330550309 |volume=55 |year=1990 |pmid=6455922 |issue=3 |pages=351–8}}</ref> Then a genetic exchange in the northern extremes introduced by the [[Thule people]] (proto-Inuit) approximately 800–1,000 years ago began.<ref name=inuit/><ref name=variation/> These final Pre-Columbian migrants introduced haplogroups A2a and A2b to the existing Paleo-Eskimo populations of Canada and Greenland, culminating in the modern [[Inuit]].<ref name=inuit/><ref name=variation>{{cite journal |last1=Helgason |first1=Agnar |last2=Pálsson |first2=Gísli |last3=Pedersen |first3=Henning Sloth |last4=Angulalik |first4=Emily |last5=Gunnarsdóttir |first5=Ellen Dröfn |last6=Yngvadóttir |first6=Bryndís |last7=Stefánsson |first7=Kári |display-authors=3|title=mtDNA variation in Inuit populations of Greenland and Canada: migration history |url=http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/journal/112214855/abstract |journal=American Journal of Physical Anthropology |year=2006 |volume=130 |issue=1 |pmid=16353217 |pages=123–134 |doi=10.1002/ajpa.20313}}</ref>
[[File:Frequency distribution of the main mtDNA American haplogroups in Native American populations.png|upright=1.25|thumb|Frequency distribution of the main mtDNA American haplogroups in Native American populations.|alt=Codes for populations are as follow: North America: 1 = Chukchy, 2 = Eskimos ; 3 = Inuit (collected from the HvrBase database ; 4 = Aleuts ; 5 = Athapaskan ; 6 = Haida ; 7 = Apache, 8 = Bella Coola ; 9 = Navajo ; 10 = Sioux, 11 = Chippewa, 12 = Nuu-Chah-Nult ; 13 = Cheyenne ; 14 = Muskogean populations ; 15 = Cheyenne-Arapaho ; 16 = Yakima ; 17 = Stillwell Cherokee ; Meso-America: 18 = Pima ; 19 = Mexico ; 20 = Quiche ; 21 = Cuba ; 22 = El Salvador ; 23 = Huetar ; 24 = Emberá ; 25 = Kuna ; 26 = Ngöbé ; 27 = Wounan ; South America: 28 = Guahibo ; 29 = Yanomamo from Venezuela ; 30 = Gaviao ; 31 = Yanomamo from Venezuela and Brazil ; 32 = Colombia ; 33 = Ecuador (general population), 34 = Cayapa ; 35 = Xavante ; 36 = North Brazil ; 37 = Brazil ; 38 = Curiau ; 39 = Zoró ; 40 = Ignaciano, 41 = Yuracare ; 42 = Ayoreo ; 43 = Araucarians ; 44 = Pehuenche, 45 = Mapuche from Chile ; 46 = Coyas ; 47 = Tacuarembó ; 48 = Uruguay ; 49 = Mapuches from Argentina ; 50 = Yaghan]]
A 2013 study in ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' reported that DNA found in the 24,000-year-old remains of a young boy from the [[Mal'ta-Buret' culture|archaeological Mal'ta-Buret' culture]] suggest that up to one-third of indigenous Americans' ancestry can be traced back to [[Eurasia#Anthropology and genetics|western Eurasians]], who may have "had a more north-easterly distribution 24,000 years ago than commonly thought"<ref name="renamed_from_24256729_on_20160803111353" /> "We estimate that 14 to 38 percent of Amerindian ancestry may originate through gene flow from this ancient population," the authors wrote. Professor Kelly Graf said,

<blockquote>"Our findings are significant at two levels. First, it shows that [[History of Siberia#Prehistory and antiquity|Upper Paleolithic Siberians]] came from a cosmopolitan population of [[Recent African origin of modern humans|early modern humans that spread out of Africa]] to Europe and Central and South Asia. Second, Paleoindian skeletons like [[Buhl Woman]] with phenotypic traits atypical of modern-day indigenous Americans can be explained as having a direct historical connection to Upper Paleolithic Siberia."<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1038/nature12736 | pmid=24256729 | pmc=4105016 | volume=505 | issue=7481 | title=Upper Palaeolithic Siberian genome reveals dual ancestry of Native Americans | date=January 2014 | journal=Nature | pages=87–91 | last1 = Raghavan | first1 = M | last2 = Skoglund | first2 = P | last3 = Graf | first3 = KE | display-authors = 3 | last4 = et al | laysource=ScienceDaily | laysummary = https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2013/11/131120133925| bibcode=2014Natur.505...87R }}</ref></blockquote> 
A route through Beringia is seen as more likely than the [[Solutrean hypothesis]].<ref name=Ancient>{{cite web|title=Ancient Siberian Genome Reveals Genetic Origins of Native Americans |url=http://www.scienceworldreport.com/articles/11062/20131121/dna-study-reveals-first-native-americans-may-have-come-from-siberia.htm|publisher=PHYSORG|accessdate=2013-11-23 |date=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref> An abstract in a 2012 issue of the "American Journal of Physical Anthropology" states that "The similarities in ages and geographical distributions for C4c and the previously analyzed X2a lineage provide support to the scenario of a dual origin for Paleo-Indians. Taking into account that C4c is deeply rooted in the Asian portion of the mtDNA phylogeny and is indubitably of Asian origin, the finding that C4c and X2a are characterized by parallel genetic histories definitively dismisses the controversial hypothesis of an Atlantic glacial entry route into North America."<ref name=Kashani>{{cite journal|last1=Kashani|first1=Baharak Hooshiar|author2=Ugo A. Perego1, Anna Olivieri, Norman Angerhofer, Francesca Gandini, Valeria Carossa, Hovirag Lancioni, Ornella Semino, Scott R. Woodward, Alessandro Achilli, Antonio Torroni|title=Mitochondrial haplogroup C4c: A rare lineage entering America through the ice-free corridor?|journal=American Journal of Physical Anthropology|date=January 2012|volume=147|issue=1|pages=35–39|doi=10.1002/ajpa.21614|pmid=22024980}}</ref>
{{clear}}

Another study, also focused on the mtDNA (that which is inherited through only the maternal line),<ref name=Tammetal/> revealed that the indigenous people of the Americas have their maternal ancestry traced back to a few founding lineages from East Asia, which would have arrived via the [[Bering strait]]. According to this study, it is probable that the ancestors of the Native Americans would have remained for a time in the region of the [[Bering Strait]], after which there would have been a rapid movement of settling of the Americas, taking the founding lineages to [[South America]].

According to a 2016 study, focused on mtDNA lineages, "a small population entered the Americas via a coastal route around 16.0 ka, following previous isolation in eastern Beringia for ~2.4 to 9 thousand years after separation from eastern Siberian populations. Following a rapid movement throughout the Americas, limited gene flow in South America resulted in a marked phylogeographic structure of populations, which persisted through time. All of the ancient mitochondrial lineages detected in this study were absent from modern data sets, suggesting a high extinction rate. To investigate this further, we applied a novel principal components multiple logistic regression test to Bayesian serial coalescent simulations. The analysis supported a scenario in which European colonization caused a substantial loss of pre-Columbian lineages".<ref name="LlamasFehren-Schmitz2016">{{cite journal|last1=Llamas|first1=B.|last2=Fehren-Schmitz|first2=L.|last3=Valverde|first3=G.|last4=Soubrier|first4=J.|last5=Mallick|first5=S.|last6=Rohland|first6=N.|last7=Nordenfelt|first7=S.|last8=Valdiosera|first8=C.|last9=Richards|first9=S. M.|last10=Rohrlach|first10=A.|last11=Romero|first11=M. I. B.|last12=Espinoza|first12=I. F.|last13=Cagigao|first13=E. T.|last14=Jimenez|first14=L. W.|last15=Makowski|first15=K.|last16=Reyna|first16=I. S. L.|last17=Lory|first17=J. M.|last18=Torrez|first18=J. A. B.|last19=Rivera|first19=M. A.|last20=Burger|first20=R. L.|last21=Ceruti|first21=M. C.|last22=Reinhard|first22=J.|last23=Wells|first23=R. S.|last24=Politis|first24=G.|last25=Santoro|first25=C. M.|last26=Standen|first26=V. G.|last27=Smith|first27=C.|last28=Reich|first28=D.|last29=Ho|first29=S. Y. W.|last30=Cooper|first30=A.|last31=Haak|first31=W.|title=Ancient mitochondrial DNA provides high-resolution time scale of the peopling of the Americas|journal=Science Advances|volume=2|issue=4|year=2016|pages=e1501385–e1501385|issn=2375-2548|doi=10.1126/sciadv.1501385}}</ref>

==Paleoamericans==
{{main|Pleistocene peopling of the Americas}}
{{see|Fuegians#Paleoamerican_descent}}
There is  genetic evidence for an early wave of migration to the Americas.
It is uncertain whether this "Paleoamerican" (also "Paleoamerind", not to confused with the term 
[[Paleo-Indian]] used of the early phase of Amerinds proper)  migration took place in the early Holocene, thus only shortly predating the main Amerind peopling of the Americas, or whether it may have reached the Americas substantially earlier, before the Last Glacial Maximum.<ref>González-José, R. et al., "Craniometric evidence for Palaeoamerican survival in Baja California", ''Nature'' vol. 425 (2003),  62–65.</ref>
Genetic evidence for "Paleoamerinds" consists of the presence of apparent admixture of archaic [[Sundadont]] lineages to the remote populations in the South American rain forest, and in the genetics and cranial morphology of [[Fuegians|Patagonians-Fuegians]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Fuegian and Patagonian Genetics and the settling of the Americas |first=George |last=Weber |url=http://www.andaman.org/BOOK/chapter54/text-Fuego/Genetics/text-FuegianGenetics.htm |publisher=Andaman Association |year=2007 |accessdate=2010-01-22 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130505072339/http://www.andaman.org/BOOK/chapter54/text-Fuego/Genetics/text-FuegianGenetics.htm |archivedate=2013-05-05 |df= }}<br/>{{cite journal  |vauthors=García-Bour J, Pérez-Pérez A, Alvarez S, etal |title=Early population differentiation in extinct aborigines from Tierra del Fuego-Patagonia: ancient mtDNA sequences and Y-chromosome STR characterization |journal=Am. J. Phys. Anthropol. |volume=123 |issue=4 |pages=361–70 |date=April 2004 |pmid=15022364 |doi=10.1002/ajpa.10337 }}
Neves W.A., Powell J.F., Ozolins E.G. 1999, "Extra-Continental Morphological Affinities of Palli Aike, Southern Chile", Intersciencia, 24/4: 258- 263.
</ref> 
Nomatto et al. (2009) proposed into Beringia occurred between 40k and 30k cal years BP, with a pre-LGM migration into the Americas followed by isolation of the northern population following closure of the ice-free corridor.<ref name=Bonattoetal2009>{{cite journal|doi=10.1073/pnas.94.5.1866|title=A single and early migration for the peopling of the Americas supported by mitochondrial DNA sequence data|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|author1=Bonatto, Sandro L. |author2=Salzano, Francisco M. |volume=94|issue=5|pages=1866–1871|year=1997|pmc=20009|pmid=9050871}}</ref>
Evidence of  people from [[Australia]] and [[Melanesia]] admixture in Amazonian populations was found  by Skoglund and Reich (2016).<ref>P. Skoglund, D. Reich,  "A genomic view of the peopling of the Americas", ''Curr Opin Genet Dev.'' 2016 Dec; 41: 27–35,  doi:  10.1016/j.gde.2016.06.016.
"Recently, we carried out a stringent test of the null hypothesis of a single founding population of Central and South Americans using genome-wide data from diverse Native Americans. We detected a statistically clear signal linking Native Americans in the Amazonian region of Brazil to present-day Australo-Melanesians and Andaman Islanders (‘Australasians’). Specifically, we found that Australasians share significantly more genetic variants with some Amazonian populations—including ones speaking Tupi languages—than they do with other Native Americans. We called this putative ancient Native American lineage "Population Y" after Ypykuéra, which means ‘ancestor’ in the Tupi language family."</ref>

Archaeological evidence for pre-LGM human presence in the Americas was first presented in the 1970s.<ref name=Cinq1979>{{cite journal|author=Cinq-Mars J.|date=1979 |title=Bluefish Cave 1: A Late Pleistocene Eastern Beringian Cave Deposit in the Northern Yukon |journal=Canadian Journal of Archaeology |issue=3|pages=1–32 }}</ref><ref name=Bonnichsen1978>{{citation|author=Bonnichsen, Robson,|title=Critical arguments for Pleistocene artifacts from the Old Crow basin, Yukon: a preliminary statement (p.102-118) |volume=''in'' Bryan, Alan L., editor Early Man in America from a Circum-Pacific Perspective. Edmonton: Archaeological Researches International (Occasional Papers No. 1), Department of Anthropology, University of Alberta, 1978}}</ref> notably the "[[Luzia Woman]]" skull found in Brazil and the [[Monte Verde]] site in Chile, both discovered in 1975.<ref>Dillehay, Tom D.; Ocampo, Carlos (November 18, 2015). "New Archaeological Evidence for an Early Human Presence at Monte Verde, Chile". PLoS ONE. 10 (11): e0141923. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0141923.</ref> Other notable sites of early human inhabitation found in North America include Paisley Caves, Oregon and Bluefish Caves, Canada.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bourgeon|first=Lauriane|last2=Burke|first2=Ariane|last3=Higham|first3=Thomas|date=2017-01-06|title=Earliest Human Presence in North America Dated to the Last Glacial Maximum: New Radiocarbon Dates from Bluefish Caves, Canada|journal=PLOS ONE|language=en|volume=12|issue=1|pages=e0169486|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0169486|issn=1932-6203|pmc=5218561|pmid=28060931}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gilbert|first=M. Thomas P.|last2=Jenkins|first2=Dennis L.|last3=Götherstrom|first3=Anders|last4=Naveran|first4=Nuria|last5=Sanchez|first5=Juan J.|last6=Hofreiter|first6=Michael|last7=Thomsen|first7=Philip Francis|last8=Binladen|first8=Jonas|last9=Higham|first9=Thomas F. G.|date=2008-05-09|title=DNA from Pre-Clovis Human Coprolites in Oregon, North America|url=http://science.sciencemag.org/content/320/5877/786|journal=Science|language=en|volume=320|issue=5877|pages=786–789|doi=10.1126/science.1154116|issn=0036-8075|pmid=18388261}}</ref>

==Old World genetic admixture==
{{details|topic=genetic admixture in the Americas|Miscegenation#Genetic studies of racial admixture}}
{{See also|Multiracial American}}
[[File:Distribution of Indigenous Peoples in the Americas.svg|thumb|upright=1.3|The current distribution of indigenous peoples (based on self-identification, not genetic data).]]

Substantial [[racial admixture]] has taken place during and since the [[European colonization of the Americas]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Newman |first=Richard |editor=[[Kwame Anthony Appiah|Kwame Appiah]] and [[Henry Louis Gates, Jr.]] |title=Africana: The Encyclopedia of the African and African American Experience |edition=1st |year=1999 |publisher=Basic Civitas Books |location=New York |isbn=978-0-465-00071-5 |page=1320 |chapter=Miscegenation |quote=Miscegenation, a term for sexual relations across racial lines; no longer in use because of its racist implications|title-link=Encyclopedia Africana }}</ref><ref name=Chasteen>{{cite book|title=Problems in modern Latin American history, sources and interpretations|first1=John Charles |last1=Chasteen|first2=James A |last2=Wood |publisher=Sr Books|year=2004|url=https://books.google.com/?id=FxRdCirZ-voC&lpg=PA4&dq=Miscegenation%20in%20the%20americas&pg=PA4#v=onepage&q=|pages=4–10|isbn=978-0-8420-5060-9|accessdate=2010-02-24}}</ref>

===South and Central America===
In Latin America in particular, significant racial admixture took place between the indigenous Amerind population, the European-descended colonial population, and the Sub-Saharan African populations [[Trans-Atlantic slave trade|imported as slaves]].  From about 1700, a Latin American terminology developed to refer to the various combinations of mixed racial descent produced by this.<ref>Chasteen (2004:4): "between the White elite and the mass of Amerindians and Negroes there existed by 1700 a thin stratum of population subject neither to Negro slavery nor Amerindian tutelage, consisting of the products of racial interbreeding among Whites, Amerindians, and Negroes and defined as mestizos, mulattoes and zambos (mixture of Indian and Negro) and their many combinations."</ref>

Many individuals who self-identify as one race exhibit genetic evidence of a [[Race and genetics#Defining race|multiracial ancestry]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Admixture Studies in Latin America: From the 20th to the 21st Century|publisher=Facultad de Humanidades y Ciencias de la Educación|url=http://www.fhuce.edu.uy/antrop/cursos/abiol/links/Artics/sans.pdf|format=PDF|year=2000|accessdate=2010-02-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717090819/http://www.fhuce.edu.uy/antrop/cursos/abiol/links/Artics/sans.pdf#|archive-date=2011-07-17|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>
The European conquest of South and Central America, beginning in the late 15th century, was initially executed by male soldiers and sailors from the [[Iberian Peninsula]] ([[Spain]] and [[Portugal]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://backintyme.com/essays/?p=5|title=Afro-European Genetic Admixture in the United States|last=Sweet|first=Frank W|year=2004|work=Essays on the Color Line and the One-Drop Rule|publisher=Backintyme Essays|accessdate=2010-02-24}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|certain=y|reason=Frank Sweet is not a reliable source. His is a self-published fringe viewpoint.|date=September 2017}} The new soldier-settlers fathered children with Amerindian women and later with [[Atlantic slave trade|African slaves]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Sweet|first=Frank W |title=Legal History of the Color Line: The Notion of Invisible Blackness|publisher=Backintyme Publishing|year=2005|page=542|isbn=978-0-939479-23-8 |url=http://backintyme.com/ad230.php|accessdate=2010-02-24}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|certain=y|reason=Frank Sweet is not a reliable source. His is a self-published fringe viewpoint.|date=September 2017}} These [[mixed-race]] children were generally identified by the [[Spanish colonization|Spanish colonist]] and [[Portuguese colonization of the Americas|Portuguese colonist]] as ''"[[Casta]]s"''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Racial Classifications in Latin America|last=Soong |first=Roland|url=http://www.zonalatina.com/Zldata55.htm|publisher=Latin American Media|year=1999|accessdate=2010-02-25}}</ref>

===North America===
The  [[North American fur trade]] during the 16th century brought many more European men, from [[France]], [[Ireland]], and [[Great Britain]], who took North Amerindian women as wives.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Red River Cart and Trails: The Fur Trade|first=Harry B|last=Brehaut|url=http://www.mhs.mb.ca/docs/transactions/3/redrivercart.shtml|publisher=Manitoba Historical Society|year=1998|accessdate=2010-02-24}}</ref> Their children became known as ''"[[Métis people (Canada)|Métis]]"'' or ''"[[Bois-Brûlés]]"'' by the [[French colonization of the Americas|French colonist]]s and ''"[[mixed-blood]]s"'', ''"[[half-breed]]s"'' or ''"[[Anglo-Métis|country-born]]"'' by the [[British colonization of the Americas|English colonist]]s and [[Scottish colonization of the Americas|Scottish colonist]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Who are Métis ?|url=http://www.metisnation.ca/who/index.html|publisher=[[Métis National Council]]|year=2001|accessdate=2010-02-24|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100226021520/http://www.metisnation.ca/who/index.html|archivedate=2010-02-26|df=}}</ref>

Native Americans in the [[United States]] are more likely than any other racial group to practice [[Interracial marriage in the United States|racial exogamy]], resulting in an ever-declining proportion of indigenous ancestry among those who claim a Native American identity.<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-14089253|title=Blood affects US Indian identity|journal=BBC News|first=Paul|last=Adams|date=July 10, 2011|accessdate=October 22, 2017|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> 
In the [[United States 2010 census]], nearly 3 million people indicated that their race was Native American (including Alaska Native).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?src=CF|title=American FactFinder - Results|first=U.S. Census|last=Bureau|website=factfinder.census.gov|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref> 
This is based on self-identification, and there are no formal defining criteria for this designation.
Especially numerous was the self-identification of [[Cherokee]] ethnic origin,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nerve.com/life/why-do-so-many-people-claim-they-have-cherokee-in-their-blood|title=Why Do So Many People Claim They Have Cherokee In Their Blood? - Nerve|website=www.nerve.com|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}
{{Cite journal|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/history/2015/10/cherokee_blood_why_do_so_many_americans_believe_they_have_cherokee_ancestry.html|title=Why Do So Many Americans Think They Have Cherokee Blood?|journal=Slate|first=Gregory D.|last=Smithers|date=October 1, 2015|accessdate=October 22, 2017|via=Slate}}</ref> a phenomenon dubbed the "Cherokee Syndrome".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyyonder.com/cherokee-syndrome/2011/02/10/3170/|title=The Cherokee Syndrome - Daily Yonder|website=www.dailyyonder.com|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref> 
The context is the cultivation of an  [[Ethnic option|opportunistic ethnic identity]] related to the perceived prestige associated with Native American ancestry.<ref name="auto">{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/21/magazine/the-newest-indians.html|title=The Newest Indians|journal=The New York Times|first=Jack|last=Hitt|date=August 21, 2005|accessdate=October 22, 2017|via=www.nytimes.com}}</ref> [[Native American identity]] in the Eastern United States is mostly detached from genetic descent, and embraced by people of predominantly  European ancestry.<ref name="auto"/><ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/03/us/03cherokee.html|title=Putting to a Vote the Question 'Who Is Cherokee?'|journal=The New York Times|first=Evelyn|last=Nieves|date=March 3, 2007|accessdate=October 22, 2017|via=www.nytimes.com}}.
[[Principal Chief of the Cherokee Nation]], [[Bill John Baker]], reported as of "1/32 Cherokee" ancestry (which would amount to about 3%).</ref>
Some tribes have adopted criteria of [[racial purity]], usually through a [[Certificate of Degree of Indian Blood]], and practice [[Tribal disenrollment|disenrollment of tribal members]] unable to provide [[Genealogical DNA test#Native American ancestry|proof of Native American ancestry]]. This topic has become a contentious issue in [[Native American reservation politics]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indiancountrymedianetwork.com/news/native-news/what-percentage-indian-do-you-have-to-be-in-order-to-be-a-member-of-a-tribe-or-nation/|title=What Percentage Indian Do You Have to Be in Order to Be a Member of a Tribe or Nation? - Indian Country Media Network|website=indiancountrymedianetwork.com|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}.
{{cite web|url=https://indiancountrymedianetwork.com/news/politics/disappearing-indians-part-ii-the-hypocrisy-of-race-in-deciding-whos-enrolled/|title=Disappearing Indians, Part II: The Hypocrisy of Race In Deciding Who's Enrolled - Indian Country Media Network|website=indiancountrymedianetwork.com|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref>

=== Ancient Beringians ===
[[File:Early migrations mercator.svg|thumb|25 kya Beringia during the LGM
16-14 kya peopling of the Americas just after the LGM]]
Recent archaeological findings in Alaska have shed light on the existence of a previously unknown Native American population that has been academically named "[[Ancient Beringian|Ancient Beringians]]."<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cam.ac.uk/research/news/direct-genetic-evidence-of-founding-population-reveals-story-of-first-native-americans|title=Direct genetic evidence of founding population reveals story of first Native Americans|date=2018-01-03|work=University of Cambridge|access-date=2018-10-15|language=en}}</ref> Although it is popularly agreed among archeologists that early settlers had crossed into Alaska from Russia through the [[Beringia|Bering Strait land bridge]], the issue of whether or not there was one founding group or several waves of migration is a controversial and prevalent debate among academics in the field today. In 2018, the sequenced DNA of a native girl, whose remains were found at the Sun River archaeological site in Alaska in 2013 (maybe add citation here), proved not to match the two recognized branches of Native Americans and instead belonged to the early population of Ancient Beringians.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://phys.org/news/2018-01-reveals-evidence-population-ancient-native.html|title=Direct genetic evidence of founding population reveals story of first Native Americans|access-date=2018-10-15}}</ref> This breakthrough is said to be the first direct genomic evidence that there was potentially only one wave of migration in the Americas that occurred, with genetic branching and division transpiring after the fact. The migration wave is estimated to have emerged about 20,000 years ago.<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cam.ac.uk/research/news/direct-genetic-evidence-of-founding-population-reveals-story-of-first-native-americans|title=Direct genetic evidence of founding population reveals story of first Native Americans|date=2018-01-03|work=University of Cambridge|access-date=2018-10-15|language=en}}</ref> The Ancient Beringians are said to be a common ancestral group among contemporary Native American populations today, which differs in results collected from previous research that suggests that modern populations were ancestors of either Northern and Southern branches.<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cam.ac.uk/research/news/direct-genetic-evidence-of-founding-population-reveals-story-of-first-native-americans|title=Direct genetic evidence of founding population reveals story of first Native Americans|date=2018-01-03|work=University of Cambridge|access-date=2018-10-15|language=en}}</ref> Experts were also able to use wider genetic evidence to establish that the split between the Northern and Southern American branches of civilization from the Ancient Beringians in Alaska only occurred about 17,000 and 14,000 years,<ref name=":4">{{Cite journal |last=Reich |first=David |last2=Patterson |first2=Nick |last3=Campbell |first3=Desmond |last4=Tandon |first4=Arti |last5=Mazieres |first5=Stéphane |last6=Ray |first6=Nicolas |last7=Parra |first7=Maria V. |last8=Rojas |first8=Winston |last9=Duque |first9=Constanza |date=2012-08-16 |title=Reconstructing Native American Population History |journal=Nature |volume=488 |issue=7411 |pages=370–374|doi=10.1038/nature11258 |pmc=3615710|pmid=22801491}}</ref> further challenging the concept of multiple migration waves occurring during the very first stages of settlement.  

==Blood groups==
[[File:Map of Group O.png|thumb|upright=1.4|Frequency of O group in indigenous populations. Note the predominance of this group in Indigenous Americans.]]

{{Further|ABO blood group system}}
Prior to the 1952 confirmation of DNA as the hereditary material by [[Alfred Hershey]] and [[Martha Chase]], scientists used [[blood proteins]] to study human genetic variation.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Hershey A, Chase M |title=Independent functions of viral protein and nucleic acid in growth of bacteriophage | url=http://www.jgp.org/cgi/reprint/36/1/39.pdf | journal=J Gen Physiol |volume=36 |issue=1 | pages=39–56 |year=1952 |pmid=12981234 |doi=10.1085/jgp.36.1.39|format=PDF |pmc=2147348}}</ref><ref name="pleiades"/> The [[ABO blood group system]] is widely credited to have been discovered by the Austrian [[Karl Landsteiner]], who found three different blood types in 1900.<ref name=Landsteiner_1900>{{cite journal | author = Landsteiner K | title = Zur Kenntnis der antifermentativen, lytischen und agglutinierenden Wirkungen des Blutserums und der Lymphe | journal = [[Zentralblatt Bakteriologie]] | year = 1900 | volume = 27 | pages = 357–62}}</ref> Blood groups are inherited from both parents. The ABO blood type is controlled by a single [[gene]] (the [[ABO (gene)|ABO gene]]) with three [[allele]]s: ''i'', ''I<sup>A</sup>'', and ''I<sup>B</sup>''.<ref name=Yazer>{{cite journal |vauthors=Yazer M, Olsson M, Palcic M |title=The cis-AB blood group phenotype: fundamental lessons in glycobiology |journal=Transfus Med Rev |volume=20 |issue=3 |pages=207–17 |year=2006 |pmid=16787828 |doi=10.1016/j.tmrv.2006.03.002}}</ref>

Research by [[Ludwik and Hanka Herschfeld]] during [[World War I]] found that the frequencies of [[blood groups]] A, B and O differed greatly from region to region.<ref name="pleiades">{{cite journal |author=LILLE-SZYSZKOWICZ I |title=Development of studies on pleiades of blood groups|journal=Postȩpy Higieny I Medycyny Doświadczalnej |volume=11 |issue=3 |pages=229–33 |year=1957 |pmid=13505351}}</ref> The "O" blood type (usually resulting from the absence of both A and B alleles) is very common around the world, with a rate of 63% in all human populations.<ref name=Blood/> Type "O" is the primary blood type among the indigenous populations of the Americas, in-particular within Central and South America populations, with a frequency of nearly 100%.<ref name=Blood>{{cite web |title=Distribution of Blood Types |url=http://anthro.palomar.edu/vary/vary_3.htm |publisher=Behavioral Sciences Department, Palomar College |year=2010 |accessdate=2010-03-14 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060221171034/http://anthro.palomar.edu/vary/vary_3.htm |archivedate=2006-02-21 |df= }}</ref> In indigenous North American populations the frequency of type "A" ranges from 16% to 82%.<ref name=Blood/> This suggests again that the initial Amerindians evolved from an isolated population with a minimal number of individuals.<ref>{{cite journal  |vauthors=Estrada-Mena B, Estrada FJ, Ulloa-Arvizu R, etal |title=Blood group O alleles in Native Americans: implications in the peopling of the Americas |journal=Am. J. Phys. Anthropol. |volume=142 |issue=1 |pages=85–94 |date=May 2010 |pmid=19862808 |doi=10.1002/ajpa.21204 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1002/ajpa.1330140217 |url=http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/journal/110524305/abstract |last1=Chown |first1=B |last2=Lewis |first2=M |title=The blood group genes of the Cree Indians and the Eskimos of the ungava district of Canada |journal=American Journal of Physical Anthropology |volume=14 |issue=2 |pages=215–224 |year=2005 |pmid=13362488}}</ref>

The standard explanation for such a high population of Native Americans with blood type O comes from the idea of [[Genetic drift]], in which the small nature of Native American populations meant the almost complete absence of any other blood gene being passed down through generations.<ref name=":5">{{Cite journal|last=Halverson|first=Melissa S.|last2=Bolnick|first2=Deborah A.|date=2008-11|title=An ancient DNA test of a founder effect in Native American ABO blood group frequencies|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/ajpa.20887|journal=American Journal of Physical Anthropology|language=en|volume=137|issue=3|pages=342–347|doi=10.1002/ajpa.20887|issn=0002-9483}}</ref> Other related explanations include the Bottleneck explanation which states that there were high frequencies of blood type A and B among Native Americans but severe population decline during the 1500s and 1600s caused by the introduction of disease from Europe resulted in the massive death toll of those with blood types A and B. Coincidentally, a large amount of the survivors were type O. <ref name=":6">{{Cite journal|last=Halverson|first=Melissa S.|last2=Bolnick|first2=Deborah A.|date=2008-11|title=An ancient DNA test of a founder effect in Native American ABO blood group frequencies|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/ajpa.20887|journal=American Journal of Physical Anthropology|language=en|volume=137|issue=3|pages=342–347|doi=10.1002/ajpa.20887|issn=0002-9483}}</ref>
{{clear}}

== European diseases and genetic modification ==
A team led by Ripan Malhi, an anthropologist at the [[University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign|University of Illinois in Urbana]], conducted a study where they used a scientific technique known as whole exam sequencing to test immune-related gene variants within native americans.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2016/11/european-diseases-left-genetic-mark-native-americans|title=European diseases left a genetic mark on Native Americans|date=2016-11-15|work=Science {{!}} AAAS|access-date=2018-11-04|language=en}}</ref>  Through analyzing ancient and modern native DNA, it was found that [[Major histocompatibility complex, class II, DQ alpha 1|HLA-DQA1]], a variant gene that codes for protein in charge of differentiating between healthy cells from invading viruses and bacteria were present in nearly 100% of ancient remains but only 36% in modern Native Americans. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2016/11/european-diseases-left-genetic-mark-native-americans|title=European diseases left a genetic mark on Native Americans|date=2016-11-15|work=Science {{!}} AAAS|access-date=2018-11-04|language=en}}</ref>These finding suggest that European-borne epidemics such as [[smallpox]] altered the disease landscape of the americas, leaving survivors of these outbreaks less likely to carry variants like HLA-DQA1. This made them less able to cope with new diseases. The change in genetic makeup is measured by scientists to have occurred around 175 years ago, during a time when the smallpox epidemic was ranging through the americas.
